This paper discusses the design and implementation of a secure hardware key exchange system utilizing physical uncloneable functions (PUFs) and noise-based logic. The paper focuses on the security aspects of the system, making it likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Additionally, the use of Kirchhoff-law-Johnson-noise (KLJN) and noise-based logic (NBL) suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also discusses the implementation of the system on a chip, which may make it relevant to the cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) and cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-categories. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the cs.ET (Embedded Systems) sub-category, given the focus on hardware implementation.
